body:
From internals.adox (and one presentation years ago):

On other evaluations, the Verilated code detects what input signals have changes. If any are clocks, it calls the appropriate sequential functions (from always @ posedge statements). Interspersed with sequential functions it calls combo functions (from always @*). After this is complete, it detects any changes due to combo loops or internally generated clocks, and if one is found must reevaluate the model again.

This seems like the evaluate flow I agree, but from the generated _eval(), I can see combo logic are evaluated firstly, which is not aligned with the wording above.

Reason asking is we have two evaluate wtice in one click tick. 

Give Verilog exmaple:
```
module TB;
..
always @(posedge clk)
    sig_dut = ...;

dut dut (.in(sig_dut), ...)

module dut(in, ...);
wire d;
d=func( in, ...);
always @(posedge clk) 
   q<= d;
endmodule
```

To write C++ TB, within the while loop we have to do:
```
while(){
   Vdut->in = sig_dut;
   eva();
   ftp->dump(mainTime);  // current simulation time
   mainTime++;
   eval();
   ftp->dum(mainTime); // advanced to the next time
}
```

If we donot eval() twice, the "d" signal change at the same time as q. I think the function of "q" is still correct, just the "d" and "q" flip at the same clock edge hints race-condition like situation. Any suggest here ?
